<p><b>Pieter Cornelis (Piet) Mondriaan</b>, after 1912 <b>Mondrian</b>, (pronounced: Dutch <small>IPA</small>:&#160;<span title="Pronunciation in IPA" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA" title="Wikipedia:IPA">[pi:t 'mɔndria:n]</a></span>, later <small>IPA</small>:&#160;<span title="Pronunciation in IPA" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA" title="Wikipedia:IPA">[pi:t 'mɔndɹiɔn]</a></span>), (<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1872-03-07"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="03-07"><a href="/wiki/March_7" title="March 7">March 7</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1872" title="1872">1872</a></span>–<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1944-02-01"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="02-01"><a href="/wiki/February_1" title="February 1">February 1</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1944" title="1944">1944</a></span>) was a <a href="/wiki/Dutch_people" title="Dutch people">Dutch</a> <a href="/wiki/Painting" title="Painting">painter</a>.</p>
<p>He was an important contributor to the <a href="/wiki/De_Stijl" title="De Stijl">De Stijl</a> art movement and group, which was founded by <a href="/wiki/Theo_van_Doesburg" title="Theo van Doesburg">Theo van Doesburg</a>. He evolved a <a href="/wiki/Representation_(arts)" title="Representation (arts)">non-representational</a> form which he termed <a href="/wiki/Neo-Plasticism" title="Neo-Plasticism" class="mw-redirect">Neo-Plasticism</a>. This consisted of a grid of vertical and horizontal black lines and the use of the three primary colours.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
